,Recommended,301650,22558045,"Posted: 21 April, 2016",all,-AW- Adretheon,"Battlezone is not a casual RTS game. Don't make that mistake coming into this game.The game's difficulty is pretty steep on some places forcing you to think about what you need and plan out a good defense and offence. Unlike most RTS ideals where rushing into battle before the AI get's its camp set, you're rewarded for planning out your base and making the right choices for your army.The storyline for the game is also really interesting. Each mission opens the storyline up a bit more, not giving you worthless side quests that have no effect on the story.Now, there are some issues, but you'll have that when dealing with older titles. The Devs have so far been pretty good about hearing everyone out and fixing what they can.I'd highly recommend this game not just cause the game itself is fun and challenging, but the odds of getting BattleZone 2 being remade the same way is better if you do. To me, BZ2 is the better of the two but this game still has its place on top.Hopefully this game gets popular again so that other Devs try their hand at FPS\RTS games, because it's a genre that doesn't get enough love."
76561198006243109,Recommended,301650,22518601,"Posted: 19 April, 2016",all,Ronin75,"I have fond memmories of this game, played it for countless hours back in school...long time ago :)It is a perfect, genre connecting mix of RTS, base building, simulation and tactical gameplay. The game was years ahead of its time. Unfortunately they don't make games like this nowadays. It's a pity since with todays technology and graphics, this would be an instant hit.The campaign(s) are well written and fully voiced. You play a commander of either the US or Soviet forces in a war for resources in our solar system, mostly on the various moons of our planets. But it is not just your standard conflict of US vs Soviet, there will be a surprise in the campaign...nuff said. :)The UI is innovative and context sensitive, which is also absolutely a must for a tactical and strategic game like this, given the orders you have to provide on the fly. Even after so many years developers still can't get UI right and given the complexity of BattleZone, it is a refreshing surprise that a 18 year old game nails it spot on.If you think that the price is too high for such an old game, let me tell you it is totally worth it. This overhaul comes with completly new models of vehicles, buidlings, surfaces and sky-boxes. It is not just a fake ""HD overhaul"". It ain't 2016 graphics but it is surprisingly pretty for a game from 1998.Two thumbs up!"
76561197972948061,Recommended,301650,22518916,"Posted: 19 April, 2016",all,ElectricFox,"An excellent balance struck between updating the graphics, screen resolution and operating system compatibility whilst staying true and recognisable from the '98 game: it plays just as well as the original.  I'm really looking forwards to the community workshop creations and some good multi-player action."
76561198006932607,Recommended,301650,22617172,"Posted: 24 April, 2016",all,Arkestra,"Battlezone was released back in 1998 and was one of the first action-RTS hybrids - it has all the usual elements of an RTS, but you command from the ground in a vehicle, fighting alongside your troops. The genre never really took off, but because Battlezone was bundled with a lot of graphics cards it reached a wide audience and gained a cult following.If you are someone who's considering buying this having played it way back when, do it. It's a reworking, not a remake, so the real BZ atmosphere is still there. The ships and buildings are all heavily redone, with much more detailed models and much larger textures. They look excellent. The terrain looks very much like it did back in the original, so it's still behind Battlezone 2, nevermind more modern titles. But all things considered, the graphics do a good job today with the update. The gameplay is as rich as ever. Multiplayer is now handled through Steam within the game, which keeps things nice and simple, with all the old options. A bomber DM is still a thrill after all these years.If you are someone who's never played the original and are wondering whether you should buy this, well don't expect it to look fresh. The developers of this update have done an incredible job hauling parts of the game into the 2010s, but there are engine limitations. Firefights are limited to a few hundred meters in distance, and don't expect detailed ballistics or other physics.The real joy of Battlezone, however, was always its gameplay, and its blend of FPS and RTS that has never really been replicated since. In each mission you will be dogfighting and base building, often at the same time. A selection of ships can be built, each of which offer different benefits, and you can kit them out with a variety of weapons. Your resources (""biometal"") are gathered by Scavengers which have an annoying habit of wandering off into dangerous areas and so need to be constantly protected. Two single-player campaigns are included, so there's a hefty chunk of content for someone who has no plans to dabble in multiplayer.At the price, this game still delivers eighteen years after its original release, whether you're looking for something new or a satisfying hit of nostalgia. Buy it."
